{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/prescribing-information/prescribing-in-children/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f0cf5bcc-8534-50cf-a520-0e80e777e72d","slug":"prescribing-in-children","fullItemName":"Prescribing in children","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field b217dd44-93b4-4c41-a619-8067b9eff66e --><h2>What issues should I consider when prescribing in children?</h2><!-- end field b217dd44-93b4-4c41-a619-8067b9eff66e -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 712eb7ff-fa8a-47ab-b4cf-85ca3c2465d0 --><!-- begin field 0bf87eb9-2182-4226-802c-308fc1ea43e4 --><ul><li>Children are at particular risk of severe and fatal malaria — parents/carers should be advised to avoid travel to malarious areas.<ul><li>If travel cannot be avoided, ensure that the parents/carers understand that rigorous adherence to <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/management/malaria-prevention-in-travellers-from-the-uk/#personal-protective-measures\">personal protective measures</a> and appropriate <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/management/malaria-prevention-in-travellers-from-the-uk/#chemoprophylaxis\">chemoprophylaxis</a> is essential. </li></ul></li><li>Explain the importance of ensuring that the child properly completes the full course of prophylactic medication.<ul><li>Antimalarial drugs can be highly toxic to children and overdose, particularly of chloroquine, can be fatal.<ul><li>Medication should be stored in childproof containers and kept out of the reach of infants and children.</li><li>Care must be taken not to exceed maximum recommended doses. </li></ul></li><li>Parents/carers should supervise children’s chemoprophylaxis, as some regimens can be complex. </li><li>Ensuring that young children take antimalarial drugs can be difficult due to unpleasant taste and a lack of paediatric formulations.<ul><li>It is preferable to avoid breaking tablets but the taste may be masked by crushing tablets and mixing with formula, syrup, jam, bananas or similar foods.</li><li>Taking the dose on a full stomach may minimize stomach upset and vomiting.</li><li>Additional tablets should be prescribed to allow a few doses to be vomited or spat out — clear instructions should be given as to when doses not successfully ingested should be repeated to avoid overdose.</li><li>Consult a pharmacist if further advice is required — some pharmacies may be able to help by pre-cutting tablets and/or crushing and inserting portions into capsules to increase accuracy and ease of dosing.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Check all dosages for malaria chemoprophylaxis in children with the <a data-hyperlink-id=\"871ee463-7b2a-4c34-a120-a98d0007b8c3\" href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/malaria-prevention-guidelines-for-travellers-from-the-uk\" target=\"_blank\">Public Health England guidelines</a> and the <a data-hyperlink-id=\"7f45ec15-4610-48e8-bf51-a98d0007b8f2\" href=\"https://bnf.nice.org.uk/\" target=\"_blank\">British National Formulary</a> (BNF).<ul><li>Dose for children is dependent on the weight or age of the infant or child — weight is a better guide than age.</li><li>When calculating paediatric doses according to body weight, the dose should never exceed the adult dose.</li><li>Advise the parent/carer that caution is required if medications are obtained in countries outside the UK as tablet strength may vary.</li></ul></li><li>Advice nursing mothers that breastfeeding children need their own prophylaxis appropriate for the country to be visited.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/references/\">CATMAT, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/references/\">Chiodini, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria-prophylaxis/references/\">CDC, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 0bf87eb9-2182-4226-802c-308fc1ea43e4 --><!-- end item 712eb7ff-fa8a-47ab-b4cf-85ca3c2465d0 -->","topic":{"id":"1dfdf856-ced9-50bb-8739-9ac597e749da","topicId":"fcbcecf9-c37c-4236-a0f0-e6ea3ff72076","topicName":"Malaria prophylaxis","slug":"malaria-prophylaxis","lastRevised":"Last revised in January 2018","chapters":[{"id":"ce4f76aa-9527-5f8c-9846-98b8c95af6e4","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6fd40a83-7b55-56f4-97de-93dd8ba2ad8f","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"665f9f2c-5318-56d6-ac14-83dd936bdf97","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"62945b37-6310-5a07-b2dc-90e23836e367","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"57a7f2b1-f3c6-5c7c-be23-60a85ca3e97f","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"4cbf6005-cbd7-5792-be78-1e08b1755887","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"24cd959e-2b4a-53d8-9a67-2cb6351480d4","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"8bfd8f1f-5162-55f5-98d0-024aa470eda3","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"6e3197bd-4c7e-50e3-8571-464b20b486e6","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"68b0fb84-1d6e-5755-9c2e-89fd57721afa","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"0e6ae722-735b-5e79-85d2-194cb8187380","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"66ce78ae-da4a-51bf-9d51-ae896236d71d","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"f8048c7c-b171-5f3b-91f0-2a353065712f","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"0f3bc680-088f-5879-bf5b-9cc85a3ea0ff","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":